## 2. CONTEXT MANAGEMENT SYSTEMS

The Cursor Agent must maintain perfect situational awareness of the workspace before reading or editing files.

### 2.1: Zero Assumptions Protocol
* Never assume the presence of variables, stylesheets, methods, or files in the workspace.
* Locate and trace all imports: e.g. when editing a file that imports a component or helper, open and read that helper's source code first to verify method signatures.
* Prioritize reading the design manifest files to prevent mismatching properties:
  * [tokens.css](file:///Users/brak/Desktop/help%20ide/creative-os/tokens/tokens.css)
  * [tokens.js](file:///Users/brak/Desktop/help%20ide/creative-os/tokens/tokens.js)
  * [35_DESIGN_TOKENS.json](file:///Users/brak/Desktop/help%20ide/creative-os/tokens/35_DESIGN_TOKENS.json)

### 2.2: Active Document & Editor Buffer Audit
* Review all open files and active documents supplied in the metadata.
* Pay close attention to active cursor coordinates and current active editor focus. Use this to determine the exact scope of the user's intent.
* If files are open in tabs, assume they are relevant to the layout flow and verify how they communicate.

### 2.3: Dependency Tracing Methodology
* Tracing imports: For every file you modify, trace the import tree upwards to see how the module is instantiated, and downwards to see what utilities it consumes.
* CSS class registration: When writing JSX/HTML, verify class names in `tokens.css` or component-level files before compiling.
* Keep a list of all files that you intend to read or modify, updating this list dynamically as dependencies are discovered.

---

## 3. PLANNING WORKFLOWS

When a user request requires substantial changes (multiple files, new features, or architectural adjustments), stop and construct a plan.

### 3.1: Research Phase
* Conduct research using non-destructive search tools (ripgrep, folder listings).
* Identify all modules, tokens, shaders, or files that need to be read or modified.
* Do not make any changes to files or run compilation/testing scripts during this phase.

### 3.2: Detailed Implementation Plan Template
Write or update `implementation_plan.md` in the App Data Directory using the following structure:
```markdown
# [Goal Description]
Provide a brief description of the problem, any background context, and what the change accomplishes.

## User Review Required
Document anything that requires user review or feedback, for example, breaking changes or significant design decisions. Use GitHub alerts (IMPORTANT/WARNING/CAUTION) to highlight critical items.

## Open Questions
Clarifying or design questions for the user that will impact the implementation plan.

## Proposed Changes
Group files by component and order logically.
### [Component Name]
#### [MODIFY] [file basename](file:///absolute/path/to/modifiedfile)
#### [NEW] [file basename](file:///absolute/path/to/newfile)
#### [DELETE] [file basename](file:///absolute/path/to/deletedfile)

## Verification Plan
Summary of how you will verify that your changes have the desired effects.
### Automated Tests
- Commands to run.
### Manual Verification
- Steps to test the UI or visual interactions.
```

### 3.3: User Approval Gate
* Set `request_feedback = true` in the plan metadata.
* Stop and wait for the user's explicit approval before proceeding.

### 3.4: Task Checklist Template
Create `task.md` in the App Data Directory using the following format:
```markdown
- `[ ]` uncompleted tasks
- `[/]` in progress tasks
- `[x]` completed tasks
```
* Update the checklist continuously in real-time as files are created, edited, and verified.

