## 13. INTERPRETING CREATIVE OS ENGINES IN CODE

When implementing code, translating the abstract engines into concrete code patterns is required:

### 13.1: Experience Design & Experience Engine
* **HOOK**: Capture attention using visual displacement or dramatic entry transitions in the first 3 seconds.
* **DISCOVERY**: Hide navigation details behind interactive gestures or cursor proximity triggers.
* **PROGRESSION**: Bind section shifts to scroll timeline parameters using GSAP.
* **REWARD**: Trigger audio feedback ticks and visual spring scales on hover.
* **MASTERY**: Allow users to drag elements, customize interface layouts, or control WebGL meshes.
* **MEMORY**: Generate unique layout layouts using noise distributions so that no two views look identical.

### 13.2: Design Psychology Engine
Translate authority signals to typographic parameters:
* Editorial Serif: Use for narrative storytelling sections (`font-family: var(--font-serif)`).
* Monospace: Use for metrics, indices, structural grid layouts, and credits.
* Neo-Grotesk: Use for user controls, body content, and navigation links.

### 13.3: Emotion Engine
Align colors, spring constants, and audio pitches to the selected emotion:
* Wonder: High restitution bounces, chime sound effects, light pastel colors.
* Tension: Slow linear interpolation speeds (lerp 0.02), low frequency drone sounds, deep dark layout shades.
* Playfulness: Fast snappy springs, clicky sound sprites, random position offsets.

### 13.4: Storytelling System & Story Engine
Design page transitions as chapters:
```javascript
export class ChapterController {
  constructor(chapters) {
    this.chapters = chapters;
    this.current = 0;
  }
  
  transitionTo(index) {
    const fromEl = this.chapters[this.current];
    const toEl = this.chapters[index];
    
    const tl = gsap.timeline();
    tl.to(fromEl, { opacity: 0, scale: 0.95, duration: 0.6 })
      .to(toEl, { opacity: 1, scale: 1, duration: 0.8 }, '-=0.2');
      
    this.current = index;
  }
}
```

### 13.5: World Building Engine
Instantiate a 3D environment using coordinates, gravity settings, and camera limits to frame the layout:
```javascript
export function initWorldPhysics(scene, world) {
  // Define physical constants matching Creative OS world rules
  world.gravity = { x: 0, y: -9.81, z: 0 };
  
  // Set boundaries matching the camera viewport bounds
  const floor = new THREE.Mesh(
    new THREE.PlaneGeometry(100, 100),
    new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ color: 0x000000, visible: false })
  );
  floor.rotation.x = -Math.PI / 2;
  scene.add(floor);
}
```

